## Migration Analysis

Your code has **4 patterns** that need migration:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| Cancellable work loop | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` |
| ThreadAbortException as control flow | `catch` block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| Thread.ResetAbort | Keeps thread alive after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` per iteration |
| Thread.Abort in Stop() | Force-kills the thread | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |

## Why Thread.Abort Fails on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. The entire preemptive model (runtime injects an exception into another thread) is gone. You **must** switch to cooperative cancellation where the worker thread voluntarily checks a `CancellationToken`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. The loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the worker to finish
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            _workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        }
        // No fallback force-kill — cooperative cancellation is the only option
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes to Dependent Methods

Your `GetNextItem()` likely blocks (the comment says so). You **must** make it cancellation-aware, or the token will never interrupt it:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, can't be interrupted without Thread.Abort
private WorkItem GetNextItem() { ... }

// AFTER — wakes up when token is cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // If using a BlockingCollection<T>:
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel

    // If using Thread.Sleep-based polling:
    while (!_queue.TryDequeue(out var item))
    {
        token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(500); // replaces Thread.Sleep(500)
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    }
    return item;
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|----------------|
| **Not passing the token to `GetNextItem`** | If `GetNextItem` blocks on `Thread.Sleep` or a bare `WaitOne`, cancellation will never interrupt it. The thread hangs forever. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always `Dispose()` it. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid swallowing unrelated exceptions. |
| **Expecting cancellation to be instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint (`ThrowIfCancellationRequested`, `Take(token)`, etc.). Add checkpoints inside `ProcessItem` too if it's long-running. |
| **No fallback for truly uncooperative code** | If `ProcessItem` calls third-party code that can't accept a token, you can't force-stop it. Move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()`. |

## Thread.ResetAbort → Loop Continuation

The old `ResetAbort` pattern let the thread survive an abort and continue looping. In the new model this is naturally handled — catching `OperationCanceledException` doesn't terminate the thread. However, since the token is already cancelled, the `while` loop exits. If you need per-item cancellation (abort one item, continue to the next), use a **per-item CancellationTokenSource** linked to a parent:

```csharp
while (!parentToken.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(parentToken);
    itemCts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)); // per-item timeout
    try
    {
        var item = GetNextItem(parentToken);
        ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!parentToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Per-item timeout — roll back and continue to next item
        RollbackCurrentTransaction();
    }
}
```

This replaces the old `ResetAbort` "keep going" pattern cleanly.
